  &lt;details open&gt;
    &lt;summary&gt;Full review&lt;&#x2F;summary&gt;
    &lt;p role=&quot;document&quot;&gt; This isn&#x27;t something you see while wine tasting. This was only discovered when I inquired more about the different woods used and how they are prepared before being used in the winery. In a nutshell, most wines use one type of wood, but possibly different vessels along the way. Del Dotti chose to use two different types of woods on the stave of a barrel. Traditionally, one would imagine using one type of wood but Del Dotti chose to use two. One being American and one being French.
  &lt;br&gt; &lt;br&gt;
  This leads to difference choices in how to create the wine. The important thing to remember is that the wood flavor is a lot strong and more unique. Thus the wine (grapes) itself need to be balanced rather than over-powering and indeed that is the case. The tannin isn&#x27;t as strong and the wood feels like the main piece with the grapes being more of the background. Usually once would except more of the flavor from the grapes but it&#x27;s well balanced with the wood.
  &lt;br&gt; &lt;br&gt;
  The wood takes center stage and defines the wine here. The start is a strong, sharp, bold American wood flavor that leads into the quieter and sweeter grape profile. The tail end is the more typical French wood oak that&#x27;s apparent in the end. It&#x27;s a very long and noticable wood flavor that carries as usual. What is unique is that it embodies these flavors without overpowering each other. This is no different than listening to a band rather than a solo. Each has it&#x27;s own merits but in this case, the group is more interesting than the individual flavor. It is possible to taste the single-oak only variants but it is not as unique or interesting.
  &lt;br&gt; &lt;br&gt;
  The price is not cheap, rather it&#x27;s the price of the two other single-oak varieities together. It&#x27;s about five hundred USD rather than about two fifty for each. Of course, there is half the quantity, rather than buying both and combining them but alas it probably won&#x27;t be the same. However, there is a price for an unique experiment
  and the experience that comes with it and in this case it&#x27;s worth it. &lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
